This course develops elementary skills in reading, speaking, understanding, and writing the Russian language. Students work with a range of authentic written materials, the Internet, videos and recordings relating to the dynamic scene of Russia today. The semester-long goal is for students to be comfortable with the Russian alphabet and be able to read simplified literary, commercial, and other types of texts (signs, menus, short news articles, short stories) and participate in elementary conversations about daily life.&#8232;
&#8232;Students described the course as “wonderful,” “interesting,” and “exactly what I was looking for.” Although the first month was frustrating to some, the class gets “easier with time,” and all students felt that they learned a lot. &#8232;
&#8232;Professor Oleinichenko is a truly exceptional instructor who goes above and beyond her time commitment to her students. She shows “passion and concerned” over whether her students grasp the fundamental material, always making herself available for help. She often meets with students outside of her scheduled office hours because she truly wants her students to learn. Even accessible late into the evening and on weekends, Professor Oleinichenko is firmly dedicated to her students’ successful mastery of Russian. Students enjoyed class, too, thanks to her “very good sense of humor” and “anecdotes of her personal history with Russia.” &#8232;
&#8232;The grading system was “a little odd,” without any discrete point system for assignments and exams. However, the instructor tended to reward most students with good grades “if they tried hard.” In general, students highly recommend this course.

